Name: WT IsPETase
Dataset Description: Wild type PETase from Indonella Sakaiensis (Is).

Name: S238F/W159H
Dataset Description: Wei et al. studied the native IsPETase and reported that it rapidly loses activity above ~40 °C, highlighting its limited thermostability (implying a low Tₘ) and thus constraining its use for higher-temperature PET degradation.

Name: T250N
Dataset Description: Hong et al. (on the newly discovered enzyme from Cryptosporangium aurantiacum, “CaPETase”) identified a candidate with a baseline Tₘ around 66.8 °C, then engineered a variant with a Tₘ of 83.2 °C and greatly improved activity at 60 °C.

Name: WT CaPETase
Dataset Description: Wild type homolog of IsPETase found in Cryptosporangium aurantiacum (Ca)

Name: WT_S121E
Dataset Description: Lu et al. (on FAST‑PETase) applied machine-learning guided engineering to improve both stability and activity of PETase; while full Tₘ numbers are less emphasized, review data list FAST-PETase among variants with elevated Tₘ (though still lower than more thermophilic cutinases) and improved solubility/yield.

Name: WP_012851645.1
Dataset Description: Erickson et al. (in their “Sourcing thermotolerant PET hydrolase scaffolds” study) screened a series of hydrolases and found one enzyme (termed “306”) with a Tₘ of 92.6 °C, demonstrating very high thermostability and solubility among natural enzyme variants.

Name: wt LCC (Tm, dTm)
Dataset Description: Tournier et al. discovered and optimized the thermophilic LCC enzyme for PET degradation, showing it retains activity up to 72 °C (near PET’s glass-transition temperature) and exhibits a melting temperature (Tₘ) around 75 °C. Their engineered LCC variant depolymerized > 90 % of post-consumer PET in 10 hours at 72 °C, establishing it as one of the most thermostable and efficient PET hydrolases reported.

Name: WT
Dataset Description:
The authors engineered the wild-type IsPETase from Ideonella sakaiensis by introducing mutations S121E/D186H/R280A, which raised the melting temperature (Tₘ) by ~8.8 °C relative to the wild-type and improved PET-degradation activity ~14-fold at 40 °C.  ￼
This variant thereby marked a significant step in increasing both thermostability and performance of PET-hydrolysing enzymes under milder conditions.

Name: WT  BhRPETase
Dataset Description: Wild type homolog of PEtase found in bacteria HR

Name: wt BhrPETase (released product yield mM)
Dataset Description: Cui et al. (on DuraPETase derived from IsPETase) engineered the enzyme using a computational “GRAPE” strategy and achieved a melting temperature (Tₘ) increase of ~31 °C relative to the wild-type, enhancing its thermostability for PET hydrolysis.
